><A HREF="gc.htm"> Of God and His Creatures</a><hr><p>
This is the answer to the enquiry, started by
Plato, <i>Euthyphro</i>, 13, 14. The answer lies in a mean
between the savage notion of gods hungering after
the reek and savour of sacrificial meats, and the 
Epicurean <i>poco-curante</i> intermundane <i>deum natura nihil 
indiga nostri</i>, set forth in Lucretius I, 61.


